import librosa
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
from scipy.signal import find_peaks

# Pitch=[] # autocorrelation to detect the dominant pitch from an audio sample
Spectral_Centroids=[] # he centroid of the wave. In other words, the center mass of audio data
RMS=[] # loudness or energy parameter
Chromagram=[]
# Tempo=[]
MFCCS=[]


for i in range (0,len(metadata),1):
    print(i)
    #pitch
    data, sampling_frequency = librosa.load(metadata['File'][i],sr=None, dtype=float)
#     auto = sm.tsa.acf(data, nlags=2000)
#     peaks = find_peaks(auto)[0] # Find peaks of the autocorrelation
#     lag = peaks[0] # Choose the first peak as our pitch component lag
#     pitch = sampling_frequency / lag # Transform lag into frequency
# #     print(pitch)
#     Pitch.append(pitch)

    #Spectral centroid
    spectral_centroids = librosa.feature.spectral_centroid(y=data, sr=SAMPLING_RATE,hop_length=8192)[0]
    Spectral_Centroids.append(spectral_centroids)
#     print("Spectral ",len(spectral_centroids))
    frames = len(spectral_centroids)
#     print("frames: ",frames)
    
    # Get RMS value from each frame's magnitude value
    S, phase = librosa.magphase(librosa.stft(data,hop_length=8192))
    rms = librosa.feature.rms(S=S)
    RMS.append(rms[0])
#     print("rms ",len(rms[0]))
    
    #Chroma feature
    chromagram = librosa.feature.chroma_stft(y=data, sr=SAMPLING_RATE,hop_length=8192)
#     print("chroma ",len(chromagram[0]))
    Chromagram.append(chromagram[0])
    
#     #Tempo
#     tempo=librosa.beat.tempo(y=data, sr=SAMPLING_RATE,hop_length=8192)
#     Tempo.append(tempo[0])
# #     print(tempo[0])

    #mfccs
    mfccs = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=data, n_mfcc=MFCC_NUM, sr=SAMPLING_RATE,hop_length=8192)
#     print("mfccs ",len(mfccs))
#     print("\n")
    MFCCS.append(mfccs)
    
    
print("Complete")

import numpy
def wav2mfcc(wave, max_len=MFCC_MAX_LEN):
#     mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(wave, sr=16000)
    features=numpy.array(wave)
#     print(features.shape[1])

    # If maximum length exceeds mfcc lengths then pad the remaining ones
    if (max_len > features.shape[1]):
#         print("length extended")
#         print(features.shape[1])
        pad_width = max_len - features.shape[1]
        features = np.pad(features, pad_width=((0, 0), (0, pad_width)), mode='constant')

    # Else cutoff the remaining parts
    else:
        print("length cut")
        features = features[:, :max_len]
    
    return features
